To judge the ETF, we shall not burden ourselves with every holding within, but focus on the foremost ten, which claim 63.58 percent of the assets. Below are these ten, with their share of the whole.

To seek how well these ten stocks embody the ETF IHF entire, we take their present percentage of assets, normalize it to a full hundred, and from there calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, were the portfolio solely these ten stocks, in the measure the ETF hath decreed through its holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are laid out in the chart below.

From this chart, it is plain that a portfolio of merely these ten holdings yields a return 6.11 percent greater than the ETF itself, a 16 percent elevation in gains. The Beta of these ten is also .12 less than that of the ETF as a whole. Thus far, it seems that a portfolio of only the top ten might offer a higher return with a lesser beta. Yet, there lurks the chance that the means of these two portfolios are not so different as they might seem.

To discern if these portfolios are indeed different, we must measure the standard deviation of each of the top ten stocks, and normalize them to a full hundred, to weigh their total standard deviation against that of the ETF IHF.

In the turning pages of time, as one stares back upon Figure 17, there comes a fall, sudden and steep, of the commuter log submissions in the third moon of the project. It was a thing that weighed heavy on the heart, the reason for which lay shrouded in the mysteries of human behavior and the cold grasp of winter upon a New England campus. The world turns somber, and the wheels of bicycles cease their turning, footsteps falter upon the frostbitten earth. December, a harbinger of semester's end, finds souls burdened with the reckoning of academic toil, the tallying of grades, and the ceaseless march toward holiday respite. In such a time, the task of recording one's passage to and fro may well have slipped beneath the currents of consciousness.

The season of festivity and flight from the halls of learning gives rise to a month-long void, a time when scholars and teachers alike find no cause to cross the threshold of the institution. The spring comes not until late January, a fact that casts its own shadow upon the number of logs that might be expected. Yet February's emptiness stands unexplained, a puzzle to confound the senses. It could be said that any endeavor born of spirit and vigor waxes strongest at the outset, only to wane as the days grow dark. In the face of such decline, we birthed the Carpool Challenge Week, a clarion call in March to stir the embers of enthusiasm, and indeed, the numbers rose anew.

The road we walked was fraught with the challenge of sustaining the flame against both the ebbing tide of interest and the peculiar rhythms of academic life. Another trial came in the form of man's affinity for the automobile, a love affair with liberty and solitude that runs deep in the veins of the land. To turn hearts toward other paths, one must offer enticements, tokens of worth. We dispensed prizes, tokens of appreciation from the local merchants of food and drink, the healers of muscle, the keepers of books, and even the great emporiums of the nation. There lingered a question, a thought unspoken—what might have been the effect of grander rewards, a fine bicycle or a car of hybrid or electric kind, to stave off the decline? The prizes, immutable through the journey, might have grown in stature as the months passed, a beacon to draw the wandering eyes. Gift cards sufficed in the beginning, but what if, come December, the promise of bicycles had been whispered, and by January, the allure of a motor car? One can only wonder if the tide might have turned, if the engagement might have risen like the sun after a long, dark night.

In the dim corridors of the Library of Congress, I found myself drawn to the flickering ghosts of early Edison films, those trick films that danced between the years of 1895 and 1901. Fifteen in all, each a testament to the art of illusion, crafted through the alchemy of creative editing. My journey through these spectral reels was not merely one of observation, but a study of their poetics, tracing the arc of their evolution and the rare deviations that emerged in the latter days of this period. 

These films stand as relics of a bygone era, bound to the stage and its ancient customs. Their frames are locked within a frontal proscenium, the camera a steadfast sentinel, unmoving, capturing long and medium shots with a steadfast adherence to the principle that one shot equals one film. Yet, as the century turned, a few dared to breach these confines, introducing the audacity of multiple shots.

The essence of these trick films lies in their setting, the interior stage framed by the proscenium's rigid boundaries. The camera remains as still as a forgotten sentinel, bearing witness to the actors' movements confined to the horizontal plane. They do not venture forth towards the lens, nor recede into the background. Such is the nature of Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where actors traverse the stage laterally, vanishing from sight without the camera's pursuit.

This proscenium's grip dictates the distance from which we view these performances, favoring long shots and, on rare occasions, medium ones. Never do we find the intimacy of a close-up, for the tradition of theater and vaudeville dictates that the audience must behold the entirety of the spectacle, framed within the stage's embrace. The actors remain in the middle ground, distant from the camera’s gaze, close-ups forever elusive.

In their simplicity, these early trick films adhere to a singular vision: one conceptual shot defines an entire film. Their brevity, often confined to a minute or less, is a reflection of this constraint, shaped by the mechanical limits of frames per second. Their narratives are mere whispers, a nod to the vaudevillian roots from which they sprang, their magic and sleight of hand captured in fleeting acts. Yet, within this singular vision lies a deception. A trick film's sole shot is often a composite, multiple exposures woven together to conjure the illusion of disappearance or transformation. Consider The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), an early example where a keen eye discerns the seam where Mary’s severed “head” enters the frame, though to the unsuspecting eye it remains a seamless tale told in one breath.

There is a certain irony in the Gothic novel, a paradox of 'Old-New,' as Ian Watt would have it, a curious dance of contradiction that finds its roots in the pages of The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This Gothic mode, oftentimes dismissed and at other moments lauded for its 'terrible sublime' nature, finds itself both shallow and profound (Burke). Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto stands as the progenitor of this curious genre, crafting from the bones of ancient and modern romances a new form of literary expression. Walpole weaves the old with the new—theatrical flourishes of yore with the mimetic whispers of nature found in modern tales—to birth what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic draws from the well of medieval theatre, architecture, and tradition—a tapestry of the past in the face of a world racing towards modernity. Even when The Castle of Otranto first saw the light of day, the term "gothic" bore the weight of many epochs and styles, a relic deemed unsophisticated against the tide of modern advancement. Yet it is this marriage of theatrical Gothic and novelistic intimacy, this journey into the psyche of its characters, that grants the Gothic its timeless resonance, lingering as both relic and revelation to readers far removed from its inception.

Within the Gothic's shadowed corridors lies the concept of chivalry, a vestige of the medieval knightly ideal, retained and reshaped in the original Gothic tale, The Castle of Otranto. For the Gothic scribe, chivalry stood as emblematic of a bygone valor and honor, a mirror held to a society perceived as lacking. Through the chivalric lens, the 'gothic past' becomes a romanticized ideal, hinting at the dawn of Romanticism, striving to elevate the present. Walpole, encircled by political strife and the shadows of unjust censure, perhaps saw in the Gothic era a moral compass, a goodness lost to his contemporary world. In his narrative, this theme finds embodiment in the character of Frederic, a figure whose chivalric virtues are heralded before his presence graces the page.

Frederic, a prince draped in traditional chivalric imagery, bears the marks of suffering and the scars of tragedy, a man thought slain by infidels. The gallant and courteous Knight emerges, exaggerated to the point of Gothic excess, a harbinger of the tropes yet to come (66).

In the quiet hours before dawn, as the world lay in the muted embrace of night’s departing shadow, the ceaseless machinery of commerce stirred to life. Supply chain management, the unheralded orchestrator of goods from their nascent inception to their final destination in the hands of the waiting customer, unfolds its complex symphony of movement and time. It was Keith Oliver, a consultant of some renown, who in the year of 1982 sought to give this grand endeavor a name. And thus, supply chain management was christened, a term to encapsulate the intricate dance of planning and execution, a means to quench the ever-thirsting needs of a world spinning ever faster.

There are six pillars upon which this vast edifice rests: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. The stewards of commerce, the managers, wield these elements like seasoned hands at the loom, weaving the fabric of satisfaction for those they serve.

Production, the first among equals, stands as the bedrock. It is here that the seeds of all that follows are sown. It is a place where questions of when, why, where, and how are answered, where the whims of the market are deciphered like ancient runes to unveil the desires of those who wait beyond. Once the market’s voice has been heard and understood, the managers set about the task of deciding what to create, how much to create, and where these creations shall spring forth. It is a delicate balance, a dance of numbers and instinct, for to misstep here is to invite ruin. 

The chosen site of production becomes a crucible where schedules are forged and machinery hums with purpose. Every cog, every detail holds weight, for the margin of error is thin, and the cost of miscalculation looms large, a specter of squandered time and treasure. I have seen this with my own eyes, in the cavernous aisles of Wal-Mart and Target, where the very air seemed to hum with the precision of well-oiled processes. There, even the uniforms bore the imprint of meticulous design, a testament to the power of order amidst the chaos.

Supply follows closely, a river of decisions that shape the capabilities of the facility, a testament to strategic foresight. Here lies the question of divisions, each with its own machinery, its own cadre of workers, and its own unique expertise. The manager, like a conductor before an orchestra, must decide which division shall take up the baton, or if the work shall find its way to other hands, other lands. This too is a choice fraught with consequence, for the aim is velocity—the alchemy of achieving quality and flexibility while keeping the relentless beast of cost at bay.

Thus, the great wheel turns, an endless cycle of creation and movement, a testament to human ingenuity and the ceaseless march of progress.

Victorian novels, with their intricate detail and focus on the aristocracy's pomp and circumstance, often seem to linger in a world far removed from the common man's woes. But there are tales that stray from this well-trodden path, tales like Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights that breathe a different kind of air. They are works cloaked in mystery and tinged with the strange, stepping away from the expected to deepen the souls of their characters, revealing the shadowed motives and tumultuous emotions that lie within.

There is a passage where young Oliver finds himself adrift in a sea of confusion. The memory of Sikes and Crackit, their arguments echoing like ghosts in his mind, and the sudden crack of gunfire that sent cries into the night. Light and chaos envelop him as unseen forces whisk him away, each vision imbued with an unyielding sense of torment that gnaws at him relentlessly.

In these novels, mystery often unfolds through dreams or dreamlike states, each serving its unique purpose. In Oliver Twist, these eerie episodes peel back the layers of Oliver's soul, exposing his pains and his dim awareness of the swirling forces around him. When the shooting incident is revisited, it's as if Oliver is caught in a fever dream, reliving the terror as he seeks aid. The passage underscores his helplessness, the events slipping through his fingers like dust, his health teetering on the brink, visions of Sikes and Crackit haunting him. The gunfire overwhelms him, his senses dulled, the unseen hand of fate carrying him away. Pain becomes a constant companion, no longer a shock but a steady drip of fear. In this overwhelming tide, the question of whose hand guides his fate rises like smoke. Certainly not his own, for Oliver seems adrift in a world he cannot command, his spirit worn down by Fagin's creeping influence. A sense of resignation seeps into him, a silent acceptance of despair, numbing his will to act, even in the face of death.

Time slips by in a haze, the day swallowed by night, a night both endless in its silence and fleeting in its passing hours.

Some years past, I found myself in the company of young minds, tending to their struggles in that after school sanctuary. My task was simple, yet profound, to guide them through the labyrinth of their studies, though English and the written word were where my own strengths lay. It was then that I was enlisted by one of the teachers to aid a young lad named Adrian. He could have been third or fourth grade, but what troubled him was the written script, letters that danced away from his understanding. It struck me, peculiar as it was, that some letters he grasped with ease while others eluded him entirely, a mystery not easily unraveled. He was of Latino descent, this I knew, yet his English was as flawless as the sky is wide. Our journey was arduous until the day his mother stepped into the room, her tongue solely Spanish, mine barely passable. But in the exchange that followed, the truth fell upon me like an unyielding weight. It was not the words Adrian struggled with, but a simple lack of familiarity with the English alphabet. Whether this revelation bore fruit for him, I cannot say, but I hold hope that his path has since brightened.

This tale I recount to cast light upon the silent barricades of language in our schools, a truth vivid in the sunlit expanse of California. It serves to remind us that the barriers are not always as they seem. A child may command the spoken English with the ease of a breeze, yet the written form can stand as an insurmountable wall. We can all agree upon the existence of this struggle, but the question remains: what is to be done? For Adrian, the remedy was simple, though not simplistic, teaching him the alphabet, the sounds. Yet for those who scarcely speak the language at all, the solution grows tangled and complex. There is no singular answer. The path lies not in one approach but in the weaving of many: dual language programs, immersion in the mainstream, the guidance of private tutors, the structure of ESL classes.

To begin with, the dual language system holds promise, not just for the Spanish-speaking child but for every child. Studies have revealed that those in bilingual programs often surpass their peers. Fear clings to this notion, whispering of wasted resources, of no gain for the majority, but such fears are unfounded. Should these programs become the norm rather than the outlier, all children would glean their benefits. Yet the question persists: how to implement this? To demand bilingualism of all teachers is to court the unattainable. But there lies in possibility the employment of aids, tutors, call them what you will, who can bridge the gap with their bilingual tongues.

From the time we are children, the tales are spun of a world beyond us, vast and incomprehensible. Some are led to the pews of Sunday school, others to the quiet refuge of a temple, while still others wander within their own souls for the truths they seek. Many take on the mantle of faith handed down through generations, while others cast it aside, denying any realm beyond their own narrow sphere of existence. We may adopt a creed only to discard it for another as the years roll on. Whatever path we choose, we strive to shape our identity through the prism of our own spiritual insights. We search for a light in the dark to lead us from shadows to the sun.

A cardinal, my father once told me when I asked his favored bird. We sat upon the porch, the rain drumming on the tin roof above as we shared our cigarettes. The gutters spilled over, drowning the plants that clung to the edge. He peered into the rain, a gaze that spoke of searching, of remembering. He had grown gaunt, his clothes hung loose, his hair thinned. Still he looked out, avoiding my eyes. I was alone, frightened, unable to voice the depth of my impending loss, for to speak it would make it real for us both. I embraced him, settled back in my chair, and inched closer to him as we watched the rain fall through the dim light of June's end.

He passed in December, five days after I'd turned twenty-two. The chemo and radiation did little but extend his suffering beyond the doctor's predictions; what worth lay in that, when it served only to prolong his pain, was beyond me. What kind of God does this, I wondered in the silence. Alone in the night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, he had ceased listening long ago.

I did not wish to watch him cross from this life to the next. So I did not. I could not bear witness to the end of the force that had given me life. I chose to remember him in his living, not his dying. Besides, I knew him better than most, better even than his kin, and I knew he would not want his only child to watch him leave this world. For three days I lay curdled on my bed, awaiting the news.

No one even called me.

In the dust and the dirt of Caroline, there was a man named John Taylor who held the banner of Republicanism like a torch against the night. A farmer by trade, his hands knew the soil and his heart knew the politics that sprouted from it. He was a voice that spoke of freedom, a voice unyielding in its clamor against the shadow of governance. His heart beat for the land, for the agrarian life which he held as the highest calling, a life that shaped his notions of sovereignty, of Constitutions, and the courts that would pass judgment.

Taylor saw the land of the United States as a blank canvas, unblemished by the weight of old traditions, ripe for the birth of a new order of self-rule. He held firm to the belief in the natural rights of man, a fragile web where the breaking of one strand could unravel the whole. These rights, he said, were sacred, not to be touched by the hands of government. In the wilds of nature, he claimed, strength and cunning ruled, but in civilization, a different order must prevail.

To forge this utopia, Taylor spoke of a government that knew the dual nature of man's heart, both the light and the dark. He was a man who saw the world in stark contrasts. "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human," he would say, his words heavy with the weight of truth. He called for principles that safeguarded the land, that nurtured the earth, and kept the greedy hand of capitalism at bay. A government of such principles, he believed, would run true no matter the hands that guided it, for the hands of men were ever drawn by self-interest. Yet, this self-interest could be a force for good, so long as it served the common weal and did not give rise to lesser tribes that thrived on the suffering of others. A vigilant eye must watch over the government, lest it stray into the mire of bad principles.

Taylor, like his fellow Republicans, was a man of strict sense when it came to the Constitution. He wished for a Federal government as limited as the words on the parchment allowed. He feared the bloat of a great Federal beast, for it would grow tyrannical, and tyranny was expensive. Yet, he knew too well the danger of reading the document without the light of its creators' intent. Even more, he looked to the Declaration of Independence as the true covenant, speaking not of one nation but of many, each a sovereign entity in its own right.

I stood and gazed downwards, the emptiness of thought echoing the view before me. My mind, detached yet aware, dissected the scene with a precision that refused to bind it to any grander understanding. Thoughts drifted through my awareness and vanished, as if my consciousness itself were but a river carrying images away. It was as though I had no thoughts of my own, merely the fluid experience of observation.

Once upon a time, an artist I knew suggested a book, The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. Since the age of six, I had harbored a desire to draw, and this book promised to unravel the mysteries from the pencil’s nature to the mind’s interpretation of lines. It spoke of framing a picture, a square reducing the complexity of a scene—say, a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen that led to a dining room—into a manageable vision, the fruit isolated on its simple plane.

But as I stared at the bowl before me, I found no artist’s frame to contain it. Overwhelmed and awestruck, I could only stand there in silent wonder. Picasso had his blue period, Monet his love of greenery, and the masters of the Italian Renaissance embraced a spectrum of colors. If I were to claim my own artistic vision, then here lay the genesis of my creation, my Work in Brown.

My fingers found their way to the chosen tool of my artistry, muscles tensing and releasing as my hand moved, the will of my mind manifesting in what could have been the pinnacle of creativity. The water swirled, placid and clear. Fragments of matter broke away, vanishing into nothingness. With a quickening pulse, my hand struck the handle once more. Still, the obstinate brown mass clung to the bowl’s base like a slug.

Mop in hand, feet planted a shoulder’s width apart, and a green tie cinching my neck uncomfortably, I frowned at the insolent heap of processed matter left as a message for those tasked with cleaning the Rite Aid restrooms. More flushes, more moments of solitary reflection, and then my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping itself until it wore a padded glove. Straightening, then bending, my hand sank slowly into the water, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey…

In the twilight of youth, where the world unfurls vast and uncharted, the young find themselves behind the wheel, teetering on the brink of destiny, and the road claims them. It is a confluence of misfortune, where the sinews of inexperience tighten their grip, and the fledgling minds of teenagers falter amidst the perilous landscape of asphalt and speed. The National Institutes of Health speak to the unfinished architecture of the adolescent brain, unfit to bear the weight of the road's hazards. Simple inexperience, a silent specter, lies at the heart of this grim equation. It not only augments the tally of the dead but also ushers forth a litany of rollovers, reckless speeds, and wayward journeys off the intended path.

In the company of their peers, these young souls often fare worse, for such is the folly of youth to congregate and dare the fates. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center has charted these waters and found a harrowing correlation between the age of those who ride alongside and the frequency of calamity that ensues.

In the sunlit expanses of California and beyond, measures have been set in motion to tether the wildness of young drivers, provisional licenses that seek to curtail their nocturnal wanderings and limit the companionship of fellow minors. Yet, these measures are but feeble barriers against the tide. The truth lies bare, that the youngest among us, by all accounts, are ill-prepared to shoulder the burdens of risk and responsibility. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman, a voice of caution, contends that even at eighteen the mantle is too great. His research, echoed in the pages of USA Today, reveals a predilection for risk, the allure of thrill that grips those not yet nineteen or twenty. It stands to reason that the granting of the wheel should be delayed until the tempest within has calmed.

Should we persist in bestowing driver’s licenses upon the young, the roads will continue to run red with tragedy, the toll climbing ever higher. By the dawn of 2010, the progeny of the Baby-Boomers will come of age, a legion of new drivers poised to take to the highways.

Legislation, clear in its intent, could forge a path forward. Schools might continue to impart the rudiments of driving, laying the groundwork for the journey ahead, yet none beneath the age of eighteen would command the power of a vehicle. A provisional permit could yet be offered, a precursor to full licensure, with requisite hours of practice, echoing the standards of states like California, with its mandate of six hours behind the wheel and fifty in the company of an adult. The statistics of death and ruin span the breadth of this land, and thus a national decree would be a prudent, perhaps necessary, shield for the youth of this nation.

This proposal, while not novel, is a call to reason, a beacon to guide us from the shadows.

This manuscript delves into the depths of Central Auditory Processing Disorder, known in the annals as CAPD. It begins with a fleeting definition, like a whisper upon the wind, before moving to the diagnostic journey, studded with the signs and signals that warn of its presence. And in its final chapters, it offers the teacher in a mainstream classroom the tools to aid those students who bear this unseen burden.

CAPD, or Auditory Processing Disorder, walks a fine line in the realm of auditory perception. It speaks of the central nervous system's dance with auditory information, the way it wields sound like a craftsman with his tools. Defined with precision, CAP stands as the sentinel of perception within the central nervous system. It concerns itself with the neurobiologic symphony that underpins processing, bringing forth the auditory potentials that hum beneath the surface (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). It is a disorder not of hearing, but of translating the world's sounds, where the brain's orchestra fails to play its part, leaving voices entangled with the clamor of the world.

The echoes of CAPD reach back to a time in the mid-twentieth century, when it bore the name "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). In the dusty corridors of research, Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari carved out tests for the afflicted children. By 1961, Kimura brought forth dichotic testing, laying bare the physiology of the Central Auditory Nervous System, a model to grasp the unseen workings of perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). The winds of change came in 1977, when a national conference ignited the flame of research into the hearts of children with CAPD.

The disorder manifests with a myriad of faces: the sufferer may wander lost in the tapestry of sound, unable to anchor their senses; they may struggle to discern between the myriad acoustic events that ripple through their consciousness; the patterns of sound may elude them; the subtle shifts in speech, like the sharp edge of sarcasm hidden in a voice, may pass unnoticed; the cacophony of the world may drown each successive sound; the clues that sound offers may wither, leaving no trace for the mind to follow; the sequence of sound may unravel, leaving them adrift upon the sea of auditory chaos (Ferre).

Diagnosis of CAPD calls for an observant eye, a systematic scrutiny of listening behavior and auditory function. Audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others gather around, employing a suite of measures to unveil the skills bound to hearing (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). From questionnaires to the silent watch of auditory behaviors, the path is one of patience. The tools are many, but none hold dominion as the key to success; the cause remains elusive. Tests lay sound upon sound, asking the patient to untangle the threads, to find words or numbers within the noise. Advanced trials record the ear's response to acoustic signals, seeking the whispers of truth within the echoes.

In the end, the tale of CAPD is one of complexity, a disorder woven into the fabric of the mind's perception of sound, its diagnosis and understanding a journey yet to find its end.

In the pursuit of a calling within the realm of social work, my path winds toward the Division of Family and Children Services, where I aim to lend a hand to the young ones beset by the shadows of abuse and neglect. To offer solace to families fraught with turmoil. The values I carry forth into this endeavor are of service, respect, and an ethical disposition, a steadfast commitment to mend the ties that bind us, and to hone my own craft in this field. These tenets are not merely the creed of social work; they are the compass by which I steer my own life.

The desire to aid others has long been rooted in my heart, though the journey remained shrouded. Through the corridors of my schooling days, I bore witness to souls fleeing their demons, denying the darkness that trailed them, some grasping at the frailest of branches to cope. It was this tapestry of human struggle that led me to seek a degree in Psychology. Yet, the road ahead was still uncertain, and upon my departure from Piedmont College in the year of 2009, I paused. That summer, as the days grew long, a friend beckoned me to her side where a boy of sixteen summers sat, nerves etched across his face. He was fleeing from the hands of cruelty, seeking refuge. The next day, the tale unfolded as he called upon the law to intervene. I found myself drawn to his family’s door, where I whispered my concerns to the officers of the law, my newly minted degree in Psychology serving as my sole credential. They bade me speak to the parents, for the law’s hands were tied. I faced them, their eyes shifting, spinning tales of their son’s supposed deceit in bringing strangers into family squabbles. It was this moment that kindled within me the fire to pursue social work, to aid children amidst such “simple” disputes.

Justice, too, stands as a pillar in the edifice of social work. Our society claims to extol the individual, yet we are shackled by the chains of convention. So why, then, do we strive to mirror one another? I stand apart, eschewing the confines of conformity. In the halls of my education, I stood against the tides of injustice: colors in my hair that defied nature, garments that echoed my spirit, and piercings that charted their own course. I allied with those who sought equality, raising my voice against the specters of racism and discrimination where'er they lurked. In the name of justice, I stand unyielding, my protest a testament to the world I seek to change.

In the quiet tapestry of night where insomnia reigns, the discourse unfolds, bearing the weight of biological and sociocultural threads interwoven. From the depths of lineage, the biological model emerges, whispering tales of genes passed down, tales of health enshrined in the flesh. The sociocultural model, in its turn, surveys the lay of the land, tracing paths through race and ethnicity, through the sprawl of demographics and the edifice of socioeconomic standing. This examination of insomnia, it peers into these lenses, each shard of research a fragment to elucidate the models’ truths and faults alike.

The specter of sleep disorders casts a shadow, from the primary afflictions to those entwined with mental maladies, and others still, tethered to ailments or substances. The Dyssomnias, they are named: Primary Insomnia, a struggle to embrace the night; Primary Hypersomnia, a battle to evade the day’s clutch; Narcolepsy, with its sudden surrender to sleep; Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, the struggle for breath in slumber; Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, the misaligned dance of time; and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified, the unnamed tormentors. Parasomnias, they dwell in the realm of the night’s aberrations, where dreams become nightmares, where terror grips the sleeping soul, where the restless walk unbidden. These are the nightmares, the terrors, the sleepwalking specters, and those unnamed. In the interplay with the mind’s disorders, sleep finds itself ensnared, the Axis I and II disorders weaving their own patterns of unrest.

The biological model, it gazes upon the tapestry of genes, the legacy of heritable threads, and the physiology etched in the body’s script. In the hidden realms of the hypothalamus, neurons, guardians of sleep and wake, hold sway. Through the lens of mice, the study peers, discerning the GABAB receptors among the orexin-keepers, arbiters of the sleep-wake riddle. Activation of GABAA, it whispers of sleep’s embrace, its inhibition, a balm for anxiety, a lullaby for rest. Baclofen, the GABAB agonist, extends the sleep’s embrace (Matsuki et al., 2009). In the echo of these findings, the tale of mice becomes the tale of humans, the genetic and environmental tapestry revealed. A flaw in this receptor, the absence of its song, might render sleep elusive without the crutch of medicine. In the sociocultural sphere, the phenotypic inheritance could spell unrest, the receptor’s change a discord in the sleeper’s life, a shadow over school, career, and the quiet rhythm of daily life.

The years have drawn on like the slow turning of the seasons since I first set foot upon the sprawling grounds of University Park. Two and a half years or four and a half semesters, whichever measure you choose, it amounts to the same span of sunrises and sunsets. And yet for all its grandeur, this place is a labyrinth, a maze of buildings and pathways that confound even the most seasoned wanderer. In those early days as a freshman, they cast me into the far reaches of East Halls, a place perched on the very edge of the campus world. Beyond it lay the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center, but they belonged to another realm entirely. To traverse from my solitary room in Stuart Hall to the distant precincts of Willard building, nestled near the heart of campus, was a journey of nearly half an hour by foot, a pilgrimage made all the more arduous by the capricious weather that haunts State College.

An alum, not so far removed from my own time, spoke of days when those dorms stood apart from the rest of the school, separated by vast stretches of barren land. But now those vacant fields have been claimed by sports grounds, imposing edifices like the new Creamery and the health services building, and a ring of apartments encircles them. As the campus swells and spills over its boundaries, the question of how to traverse its ever-expanding domain grows more pressing. What then is the remedy for this quandary of mobility? On this collegiate landscape, it is the bicycle. Yet the mere presence of bikes is not enough. Students must take to them, and the pathways of the campus must accommodate their passage.

I spoke with a friend who had returned to the saddle after years of neglect. He mused why he ever forsook the bike. "They're a marvel," he confessed. "For a spell, it wasn't the fashion to ride, but it's the only way to get around." Beyond the boon to one's health, bicycling stands as the most expedient mode of travel. With a humble bowl of oatmeal and the strength of one's limbs, thirty miles can unfurl beneath the wheels. Like many in the throng of undergraduates, I have taken up residence off campus, a distance from the core as remote as some dormitories. The wisest choice I made this year was to acquire a bicycle. Each day finds me bound for classes in the Thomas building, a trek of twenty-five minutes on foot from where I dwell. But on a bike, that time shrinks to a mere five minutes, if the pedals are spun with vigor.

There lies the trouble, though. Pollock Road is the most direct path to Thomas, yet it is fraught with obstacles, be they on wheels or otherwise. There is merit in walking, I acknowledge, but time is a luxury I cannot afford. Absent the bike, walking would be my sole recourse to reach my classes. Such a journey to Thomas would siphon an additional thirty to forty minutes from each day. That accumulates to over two and a half hours in a week, time that is a precious commodity I cannot squander.

In the world spun by Aldous Huxley, there lies a silent thunder of machines and the cold arithmetic of capitalism that forge a dystopia, not a world but a cage of minds. The people therein have traded the soul’s solitary light for the dull glow of communal belonging, molded from the cradle to seek only the fleeting balm of happiness. They move like chessmen on a board, beneath the shadowy hand of the World Controller who dictates their fate. Through the lens of Marxist theism, one peers into the depths of Huxley’s suspicions, where the gears of nascent economies grind with ominous portent. Words of Marxist faith—homogeny, reification—echo through these pages, marking Huxley’s tale as a scornful hymn to the faults in the burgeoning economy of his age.

Capitalism, a specter of satire, is laid bare through the Marxist notion of false consciousness. The common folk, blind to the chains that bind them, see only their own gain, their vision clouded by the hands that steer them. Ideology, a shroud cast upon the laborers, molds them as surely as the conditioning in Huxley’s world. The Deltas, Gammas, and their ilk possess no will of their own; hypnopædia has sewn within them a ravenous urge to consume, to spend, to drown in indulgence. All this, the handiwork of the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea of one class wielding dominion over another, reigns supreme. The lower rungs of society, oblivious to the strings that bind them, quite literally 'buy into an ideology that supports that structure'—the twin idols of capitalism and consumerism. The higher echelons, the Alphas and Betas, perhaps glimpse the truth but remain unmoved; few, like Bernard, dare to question their ordained place. The dance of the classes is a grim ballet, whispering of the yoke of capitalism.

In this new world, true kinship between individuals is a ghostly memory. Huxley’s pen draws characters without distinction, shallow forms even among the central players. Perhaps in this, a warning—technology and capitalism have robbed man of will and voice. Love is but a forgotten fable, emotions dulled to shadows. Interactions drift on the surface, men speaking of women as one might of objects, and women recounting their liaisons without shame or depth. The placid acceptance of each class to their lot in this hierarchy lays bare the corrosive hand of capitalism. Their unwavering devotion to their role within the collective mirrors the Marxist lament of the proletariat, assured falsely of their own supremacy so long as they consume, obey, and march in step with their fellows.

It was near four years past I sat in a course on Islam at the college. The discourse was often aflame with the question of whether Islam bore hostility at its heart. And now more than ever this question seems to echo in the corridors of time. Since the shadow of September 11th fell across the world, I have watched the media change its tune from one of suspicion to a tolerance most extreme in the land of America. In those days of 2001 who could have imagined a man named Barack Obama, with whispers of Muslim lineage in his blood, would stand as a presidential candidate.  
The life of the Prophet holds a strange fascination. What I know of Muhammad’s history seems at odds with the tales told. I had learned he was a conqueror, bending tribes to the will of Islam. Yet the stories paint him as a martyr misunderstood, humble before others, and through him, they claim the truth was revealed and souls sought him of their own accord.  
There are echoes of another ministry, for the miracles of Jesus and Muhammad share a kinship uncanny. The tale of multiplying mutton and milk for forty men rings familiar. Such tales weave a tapestry of a humble prophet, one who need not prove himself but simply lived in truth and miracles. Yet I see a danger in this narrative, an attempt to eclipse the miracle of Christ by another’s hand.  
The stories are told as if to bear witness, to show how Islam won souls by its own light. Yet the tales come from afar, third-hand whispers from a murky past. This chain of hearsay does little to convince, casting shadows on the truth it seeks to illuminate.  
What gnaws at me most is the attempt to raise Muhammad as a paragon of humility and grace. Yet history wears a different face, one that speaks of conquest and power. And I wonder if those who follow know the truth of the man who stood at the dawn of their faith.

In the dim corridors of history, the teachings of the Nazarene lingered like whispers carried on the wind, yet as the ages unfurled, the faith bore forth on the backs of men drifted from its ancient moorings. The course of Christianity, set adrift upon the tides of time, found itself wandering from the shore of its inception, a pilgrim on a journey it did not recognize. In this modern epoch, a world awakening to itself, there stirs a yearning to cast off the shadows of doctrine piled high through centuries, to peer into the heart of the faith as it was known in its nascence. The old ways, held tight by those anchored in tradition, may yet fade into obscurity beneath the swell of this awakening tide.

In the hearts of believers, a profound historical consciousness will awaken, a longing to sift through the layers accreted over time, to reach the bedrock of the words spoken by the man from Galilee. It is a slow dawning, this return to the beginning, like the inexorable turn of the heavens. A movement will rise, shedding the vestiges of doctrine as a serpent sheds its skin, revealing beneath the simplicity of a truth once spoken plain. As this current flows through the lands of America and Europe, it shall gather its own, calling them to worship as in those ancient days, wherein the teachings of Jesus alone shall guide them. The institution of the church will endure, a lighthouse to navigate these strange waters, but the vast tapestry of belief shall weave itself into a singular thread, drawing the disparate strands of Christendom into a unified whole.

History holds its reversions close, and in its annals are tales of empires that once despised the cross, now bearing it high. There was a time when the Roman Empire itself turned from persecutor to patron, and likewise has this land seen its own reversals, from the chains of slavery to the halls of leadership. The coming reversion shall be played out upon the stage of faith, unraveling the skein of history in pursuit of its source, and in this unraveling, diversity shall yield to unity. It is a journey made possible by the reading of the Nazarene’s words not as ironclad decree, but as parable, as metaphor to guide the soul.

To understand this path, one must trace it to the wellsprings of belief, to the days when only the faith of Abraham held sway. The roots of monotheism, the divine whisperings of revelation, and the authority of the ancient scriptures bound the people as they stood beneath the Roman yoke in days long past. Yet even then, the people were not of one spirit, divided as they were into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the common folk who tilled the land and kept the faith in their hearts.

In the heart of The Jungle, there lies a truth as grim as the soot that clings to the factory walls. The nature of men, Sinclair shows us, is a thing of hunger and want, driven by a greed that knows no bottom, a self-centeredness that casts no shadow but its own. They seek only to elevate themselves, to carve out a piece of the world where they might reign unchallenged, giving no thought to those who toil beneath them. The great factories rise against the sky, their chimneys like the spires of some dark cathedral, belching smoke that trails away to the ends of the earth. The owners and managers, these sovereigns of soot, care little for the lives ground beneath the wheels of their ambition. The smoke, the filth, the ruin of both man and beast—these are the casualties of their progress, and they are blind to it all.

Sinclair pens a world where money is the only measure of worth, where loyalty and decency are ground down to dust beneath the relentless press of the dollar. The workers, mere cogs in this vast machine, are driven to their limits, cast aside without thought or recompense when their use has faded. In this era, the law is a ghost, offering no comfort, no justice to the laborers who sweat blood to line the pockets of their masters. The managers wield power like a lash, demanding ever more from their workers, who toil in conditions that would break a lesser soul. Sinclair does not need to speak it plainly; the truth hangs heavy in the air. The people of Packingtown, chained to their misery, have no recourse, no refuge. They are slaves in all but name, trapped in a cycle of exploitation from which there is no escape. The unions, those promised saviors, are but another cog in the wheel, thriving on the desperation of the very souls they claim to protect. And so, in this grim dance of power and poverty, Sinclair paints a portrait of a world where men are as brutal as the masters of old, and where the soil of human dignity is forever stained.

In the realm of dreams where Edgar Allan Poe found solace, he crafted "Dream-Land," a poem he held in high esteem among his works. Within its lines, the word "Thulé" appears, a relic traced by Mabbott back to Virgil. An island cast north of Britain, a terminus of the known world as the Greeks reckoned. And though Virgil’s hand etched it into history, another source, more contemporary, beckons for recognition. Poe's fascination with the Germanic writers of his time is no secret.

This reference bears weight, revealing Poe's acquaintance with Goethe’s prose. Karl J. Arndt, in his treatise "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," sheds light on the echoes between their verses, deducing an imitation of Goethe by Poe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature paints Goethe as a luminary, his "Faust" a poetic drama unfurled in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second at death's door in 1832. Nestled within the second part lies "The King of Thulé," a tale of a monarch who, upon his queen's demise after gifting him a goblet, drowns in drink and sorrow. The king, in his twilight, bequeaths all save the goblet, his steps leading him to a cliff where he casts it into the sea, shuts his eyes against the world, and follows into oblivion. The kinship between Poe's king in "Dream-Land" and Goethe's Thulian sovereign is undeniable, perhaps a dark reflection of Poe’s own losses and solace in drink. Faust too found its way into romantic drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, a mere year before Poe's own invocation of Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Twice does Thule emerge from Poe’s pen, a specter in his collected works. "Ultima Thule" finds mention in "The Pit and the Pendulum," yet it bookends the stanzas of "Dream-Land," binding them. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" echo each other, kindred spirits. Within "Dream-Land," the narrator speaks of Thule’s dark, solitary expanse, haunted by the specters of deceased companions, a world drained of color. Goethe’s king, bereaved of his queen, wanders that same shadowed realm, bereft of purpose or the will to reign. The poem unfolds as if the speaker wanders through Goethe’s lament.

Goethe’s presence looms large, an author of significance whom Poe surely knew, if for nothing but his reverence for Tennyson. When asked of Tennyson, Poe's respect was clear, and through Tennyson, Poe’s exposure to Goethe was assured amidst the many renditions that followed Goethe’s original works.

Beneath the indifferent sun of California law, could a soul, battered and broken upon the slick betrayal of an applesauce spill within the confines of a grocery store, lay claim to punitive reckoning by baring the malice of a manager who, twice warned of the peril, chose instead the company of his supper over the sanctity of the floor? A judge may well ponder before casting aside Jennifer Palmer’s plea for punitive redress. To conjure such a claim, a plaintiff must weave a tapestry of evidence, one that paints the defendant’s deeds in hues of willful disregard for the looming specter of harm, and moreover, that these deeds were steeped in despicable intent. Palmer, she can say that Martin, the manager, should have known the peril that brewed in that untouched spill, for others had fallen in those same aisles, in those same recent months, and with that knowledge, he chose yet to turn his back. Her claim of despicability, though perhaps not the strongest note in her lament, does carry weight, given the history of six such incidents in 2009, and Martin’s continued neglect to guard his domain.

On the thirteenth day of October, as the clock struck five in the evening, Rich Wayne, a humble servant of D&D Markets, came to Martin, the manager, with word of the treacherous spill. Martin, engrossed in his repast, dismissed the warning with a wave and words that spoke of no time for trifles. A quarter-hour passed, and Mary J. Haddigan, another voice of caution, approached, only to be met with the same indifference. And so at half-past five, Jennifer Palmer met her fate upon the applesauce, the floor rising up to meet her with a cold embrace, leaving her with a grievous wound in her back. Before her fall, five others had met with the unforgiving ground in that year alone. Now Palmer stands against D&D, seeking recompense and punishment for her suffering, as we ponder the merit of a motion to strike down her claim for punitive judgment.

In this land, a plaintiff may reach for punitive recompense in the breach of an obligation not bound by contract, should the defendant’s actions be forged in oppression, fraud, or malice. California Civil Code § 3294(a) speaks of malice as an act intended to wound, or lacking such intent, one must show deeds of despicable nature committed with eyes wide to the danger and yet willfully blind to the rights and safety of others. Courts have called actions malicious when they dance with disregard upon the rights of the plaintiff, when the defendant, aware of the peril their conduct births, steps forward with deliberate abandon. Such is the tale of Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., where the dance of danger was laid bare.

She had always felt a longing, an unyielding desire that could not be sated. It began when she was fourteen, just stepping into the tumult of adolescence, and it lingered still at seventeen. Over the years, she discerned that what she sought was not a thing but a person. Yet no boy stirred her heart. Some were drawn to her, stumbling through clumsy gestures to win the unwinable, but none captured her fancy. Often she pondered this enigma, searching for a cause to her strange detachment from the affairs of teenage girls. The years of reflection offered theories, but none sufficient to settle her speculation. And so she moved through life, ever questioning her own desires.

A day at home was typically a tranquil affair. Her parents were gentle souls, calm in their ways, and disputes were a rarity. The only discord came from her insistence on independence, a spirited daughter of placid parents, her lively nature a counterpoint to their serene energy, endearing her to many for her warmth and amiability.

But today was not a day of peace. As she wandered from room to room, seeking some spark of inspiration, a cry echoed from the kitchen, her mother's voice sharp and pained. She dashed to the source, fear mounting as she called out, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" There lay her mother on the floor, grimacing with each labored breath, a repeated "Ow" escaping her lips. The daughter knelt beside her, reaching out with trembling hands to offer aid. "Ouch... swee - ty, I... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words came hurried and strained, and the daughter saw the depth of her mother's agony. "Okay Mom, just tell me how to help." Her mother gestured, and the daughter, grateful for the strength she had cultivated, hoisted her and bore her to the car, laying her gently in the back before driving with haste.

The hospital was a place of sterile scents and quiet dread, but she was too consumed by her mother's plight to notice. She carried the injured woman inside, her voice rising in urgency as she called for assistance. Concerned faces appeared, and a rolling bed was swiftly brought forth to bear her mother away. The doctors whisked her into care, leaving the daughter alone with her worry.

Her mother had fallen from a stool while reaching for a vase in the high cabinet, a simple misstep that had led them here.

The study sought to lay bare that the faithful adherence to a Mediterranean Diet, as it is known, might bear upon the heart in ways that the heart might be grateful for. There is talk of a score they call the alternate Mediterranean diet score, and it speaks to a lessened chance of the maladies of the heart and the blood. This diet is a thing of moderation, of green things and fruits and nuts and grains, and the sea’s bounty, and it is a diet that shuns the flesh of beasts and the fats that come from them. The spirits are not forbidden but are to be taken with a measure of wisdom.

The old studies spoke of the diet's power to ward off death, both from the heart and from life itself, and there was one that took men and women and showed how they were bettered by it more so than by the absence of fat alone. Yet none had turned their eye toward the stroke or the death by stroke.

Here in this work, they followed the lives of women, thousands upon thousands of them, nurses all, from the places in this country where they toil. For years they were watched, their diets measured by their own hand in the telling of what they ate. And most did not falter from this task. Their afflictions were noted, the heart's struggles, the strokes, the deaths that followed. Where proof was absent, judgment was made by what was probable. They counted the weight of their bodies, the smoke of their breath, the medicines they took, and the life they lived outside of their work.

In the end, they sought to see the truth of the diet’s score and how it related to the heart and its failings, whether they led to death or not. And what they found was a thing of note. Those who held fast to the diet stood apart from those who did not. They walked a path less fraught with the troubles of the heart and the stroke. And the numbers they found told a tale clear and stark. Among the women who held the diet dear, the chance of such afflictions was lessened, the risk they bore was a shade lighter than those who did not.

The sign held aloft reads, Hitler is alive in Burma. 

Ellen Page, famed for her role in Juno, stands solitary on a corner, the cardboard placard raised above her in defiance. The message scratched out in ink, a testament to the times. Burma, or Myanmar as it is known, lies in the grip of a tyrannical junta. A power seized through a coup d’état in the year of our Lord nineteen sixty-two. Two thousand seven brought the rumblings of dissent, the first to stir in a decade. Monks clad in saffron robes led the way, their uprising named for the very color that adorned them. Saffron Revolution, they called it. At first, it was a peaceful clamor, the junta begrudgingly looked on. But peace is a fragile thing. Soon the violence swelled, an all-out war some called it, monks against the junta's might. Monasteries fell beneath the military's heel. Foreign eyes were silenced, journalists shackled or shot. Kenji Nagai, a Japanese chronicler of truth, fell on the twenty-seventh of September, slain for bearing witness. Officially, thirteen souls were lost, but Colonel Hla Win, who turned from the army's ranks, spoke of thousands more, uncounted by any ledger.

Such tales are not new to this world. The craving for power and control over one's kin stretches long as the history of man. Emperors of Rome claimed divine right to rule, to command every facet of life under heaven's gaze. In Japan, the emperors were gods incarnate, or so the tale goes, leading their people with cell phones and ritual suicide. Our own President, George W. Bush, finds counsel with Ted Haggard, shepherd of the simple, a jesting arm of the Republic's hold.

There are incidents well remembered, the protest in Tiananmen Square, June fourth, nineteen eighty-nine. Intellectuals, workers, and the young stood against the iron hand of governance. The count of the dead is a thing of mystery, the Chinese state claiming hundreds, while whispers from the Red Cross speak of thousands. And Rwanda, in the nineties, where Hutu blades and bullets sought the Tutsi, a genocide driven by the hand of government. The Third Reich, a dark chapter written across Europe, where Jews were hunted and slain, a grim testament to man's capacity for cruelty.

In the world of jazz where the shadows fall long and the nights stretch deep, Duke Ellington stands as a testament to time, a figure whose music whispers the tales of an era. His life spans the epochs of jazz, shaping an orchestra like a sculptor working marble, each note a chisel strike. The piano was his quiet companion, present yet unobtrusive in the symphonies of sound he conjured. As a composer, Ellington wove tapestries of melody and harmony, each thread a testament to the talents of his band. He built spaces where the music breathed, where soloists could wander and improvise, yet he penned orchestrations so tight they sang with the voices of the men who played them. In this, he was more than a composer; he was an architect of sound, crafting the very soul of the orchestra, each piece a testament to originality and coherence.

The pages of the Grove Music dictionary speak of Ellington’s innovation, calling upon the memory of "Creole Love Call," wherein the voice itself becomes an instrument, a whisper of the divine. Here, the voice adds texture and color, unburdened by the weight of words. It is an early glimpse into his genius, the ability to weave the voice with the style of his soloists. In the slow drawl of twelve-bar blues, the piece unfolds in six choruses:

Chorus 1: The voice dances with reeds, smooth then rough, a call and response like the wind caressing the leaves.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet takes the stage, unraveling the melody, blue notes hanging like ghosts in the night.
Chorus 3: The clarinet sweeps high, a bird's cry, supported by the piano's gentle syncopation.
Chorus 4: The full band returns, echoing the first chorus, brass and reeds locked in a conversation.
Chorus 5: A crescendo, reeds soaring, the brass and rhythm sections punctuating with syncopated stop time.
Chorus 6: Back to the beginning, but now the voice growls, an instrument in its own right.

A brief tag, a vocal run, and the trombone’s dissonant end—a whisper of mystery. Ellington’s voice, a hue in the palette of his music, a signature that permeates all he touched.

A year hence, in "Hot and Bothered," Ellington marries orchestration with the color of tone. Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat weave a tapestry, the voice and horn indistinguishable, a rich sound that echoes through the night. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" builds upon these foundations, Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton’s muted trombone a herald of melody, a mainstay in Ellington's kingdom of sound.

The question of why organisms evolve as they do is a murmur in the backwoods of science, a whisper among the trees. Are there unseen hands that guide the course of change, silent laws that bind the paths of life's unfolding? The old scholar D'Arcy Thompson, back in the year of 1917, spoke of the limits of our dreams, how the shapes of the simplest of creatures elude the tongues of numbers. Yet here we stand, no closer to the heart of that mystery. In recent days, the minds have turned to numbers and equations to grasp the ways of mollusks, their shells spun from the thread of time across the ages. We work to unravel the dance of Prunum, to see how their forms are born and reborn, and what forces shape their journey from the past to the now. Through the lens of an X-ray, we capture their secrets, the curves and lines that tell their tale. These we feed into machines, in the manner of CerioShell, to conjure visions of shells that might have been, and might yet be. The fruits of these labors we weave with the hands of experiment and description, to glimpse the greater story of their kind.

In the mind’s eye, a shell is a corridor of time, a spiral staircase that winds through the vault of the heavens. Each turn, a whorl, encircles an axis unseen, the columella, the spine of the thing. The whorls grow in their own time, marked by sutures like the rings of old trees. The greatest of these, the body whorl, stands last among its fellows. The spire is all that came before, rising to its pinnacle, the apex, and falling to its base. The creature lives within, reaching out through its door, the aperture.

We gaze upon these shells from all angles—apical, basal, apertural, abapertural. The common view, apertural, with the aperture facing you and the apex reaching skyward.

Counting the whorls is a simple rite. Begin with the apical view, find the first suture's start. Draw a line asunder the shell, counting from this mark, quarter whorls as they go.

Imagine the shell as a series of doorways, traversing time and space as the creature builds its house. You may follow this path, mapping the journey of each whorl’s heart, the breadth and height of the aperture.

This path may be drawn upon paper or inscribed in the language of numbers. With these symbols, the story of the mollusk’s shell is written, and by their alteration, the tale may change.

In that land stretched across the equator where the sun met the sea, the cries of newborns had not changed much in ten long years. Indonesia, with its archipelago of islands and dreams, found itself on the road to meet the world's grand visions, those Millennium goals. Yet, for the mothers and their children, the road was long and fraught with shadows. The water was cleaner, the latrines dug, but the health of the young and the bearing women lagged behind, like ships in a calm sea, missing the wind to carry them forth to the year fifteen of the new century.

The tale of healers attending births was one of numbers that shone but with a dim light. Seventy-two in a hundred births now saw a skilled hand, but many were still the hands of tradition, the midwives who could not mend what went awry. And so, the blood flowed and lives ebbed with it, the truth of numbers laid bare. The healing of the young, too, fell short as fewer children were brought to the healers when sickness struck. The records of care after birth were but whispers, incomplete and worrying, a story untold but known.

In the cities, the knife of the surgeon came to bear upon seven in a hundred mothers, but in the countryside, only two. The chasm between the town and the field was vast, like the gap between the rich man's house and the poor man's shack, where a quarter again and some more could not find a healer at all. The cost was counted in coins and lives.

The question that lingered in the air was how to mend what was broken. Should the land craft new ways, specific and clear, or should it weave a stronger cloth for all, where mothers and children found care before and after the birthing? The allure of quick fixes was strong, a temptation like the siren's call, but the wisdom of the land cautioned against it. To pour all into one cup left others dry, and healers would gather where the gold shone brightest, leaving the rest to wither. The tale of the world’s fight against the plague of AIDS was told, and the lesson of family planning left behind was learned. To run many races at once was to tire and falter, the weight of forms and ledgers heavy on the mind and hand.

And so, the path lay open, a choice between the quick and the lasting, the easy and the just. The land would choose, as it had always done, with the wisdom of its elders and the hope of its young.

In the vast sprawl of time, popular music has unfurled itself like an unending tapestry, its threads woven into so many genres that to enumerate them all is a task of futility. Such is the nature of things, for from the root of each genre—be it rap, rock, country, jazz, folk, to name but a few—sprout myriad offshoots, each branching into its own sub and sub-sub genres, a fractal of sound and thought. Among these, heavy metal stands as a testament to the wild diversity and raw expressiveness of popular music over these past forty years. It is a genre of emotion, stark and unyielding, often dwelling in the shadowed corners of the heart. Diverse too, for the genre, almost from its inception, revealed itself pliable, a clay for the sculptor's hand, birthing sub-genres and sub-sub-genres in an ever-expanding lineage that persists to this day.

And now, in this age, heavy metal has become a labyrinthine creature of many faces. It is a confluence of themes borrowed from other musical realms, yet it is not without origin. To comprehend the metal that pervades the airwaves now, one must gaze into the heart of the metal movement itself, understanding it as a force, a revolution rather than merely a sound.

Metal, in its essence, is a movement shaped by the darkness. It is a music of excess—more bass, more volume, more ferocity, more drama. It eschews simplicity in favor of skill; those who wield its instruments do so with masterful hands, their prowess evident in each note. Unsurprisingly, it is a movement steeped in the haze of drugs, the psychedelic tempest of the mid-seventies having driven artists to the edge of sanity, birthing records that seemed not of this world, their madness attributed to the substances that fueled them. Its qualities are dark, visceral, a stark contrast to the brighter hues of popular music that came before. Later generations of metal drew from the Romantic era's somber depths, echoing its darkness and intensity in their own creation. The lyrical darkness, as expressed by Byrne, is a cornerstone of this movement.

Consider the song Helter Skelter, a glimpse into the darker psyche of the Beatles. It is a sonic rollercoaster, its undulating rhythm a nod to the chaos of drug-fueled perception. This track is oft hailed as one of the progenitors of heavy metal, a retort to the weighty, shadowy tones of a Rolling Stones song. The Beatles, in their ambition, sought to prove their mettle, planting this song like a flag upon The White Album's expansive terrain.

In the years before the Surrealists laid down their dreams in paint, Henri Rousseau, a man given to his own visions, conjured dreams both in the flesh and in the mind. The Dream, a canvas birthed in 1910 by Rousseau's own hands, whispers not only of a woman transfixed amidst the wild wonders of her slumber but also of Rousseau's own aspirations. He yearned, from the first stroke of his brush, for the acknowledgment of those who tread the hallowed halls of art; for the embrace of the world he adored from afar. It was an arduous path he walked, torn between the decision to echo the masters and thus gain entry into their circle, or to wander a solitary road, painting as the muse willed, unshackled.

To understand this struggle woven into The Dream, one must peer into Rousseau's own tale. Born in the spring of 1844, in the modest town of Laval, northwestern France, he was the son of a tinsmith whose trade brought modest comfort. Rousseau's education was not in the arts, but in the mundane service of tolls and tariffs, until the age of forty, when fate's cruel hand left him bereft of his beloved Clémence and all but one of their children. It was grief that led him to the canvas, seeking solace and rebirth in the pigments and the brush, a refuge from the world’s harshness. Unlike his peers, who painted the peasant with romantic eyes, Rousseau painted with the sincerity of one who knew the common lot of man.

The yearning Rousseau felt for acceptance among the art world's elite is a longing that can be understood in the scope of his life. An outsider, self-taught, entering the arena of art at an age when many are well settled into their craft, he labored alongside giants whose names echoed through the salons. It was only as the likes of Matisse began to ascend that Rousseau's own star flickered into notice. In the pages of Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon speaks of these two men, not as rivals, but as travelers on different paths. Matisse, wary of the familiar, sought to avoid the trite, while Rousseau, in his heart, wished only for a place among the accepted, to paint with such convention that he might secure his seat at the table of the Artiste Français.

In the vast expanse of human thought, many a thinker has pondered the kinship between ethics and aesthetics, truth and beauty. There lies, I reckon, a reason deep in the marrow of existence for this bond. As Keats mused in his "Ode on a Grecian Urn," beauty and truth are entwined, inseparable. Much of what we glean from life comes through the hard school of experience or the guiding hand of education. Yet, there is a curious appreciation for ethics and aesthetics that needs no such tutelage. They exist as if waiting to be discovered, not instructed. In their essence, they seek to describe rather than prescribe. Our reckonings with morality and beauty are endeavors to understand why a painting or a tale is beautiful or why an act is moral, not a ledger of rules to craft such things.

In the realm of critique, words fall short of capturing the true essence of what is good or beautiful. Take da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for instance. Discussions may swirl around its composition or the mysteries it holds, but these fail to truly explain its greatness. When asked about a beloved work of art or literature, folks often say, "There's just something about it," before delving into the why of it all. Art and morals elude complete reduction to mere descriptors of their traits. As Flannery O'Connor put it, stories say what cannot be said otherwise; they speak truths beyond the reach of mere statements. No matter how we dissect a literary work, a fragment remains, transcendent and untouched. Ethics shares this ineffable quality. Wittgenstein tells us ethics cannot be expressed, for it is transcendental. This elusive "something," this je ne sais quoi, is the shared power of art and morality, binding them together in their timeless dance.

For morality and art are bound by their profound impact on us at a level that defies explanation. They speak to us in a language beyond words, touching the very core of our being. This bond is perhaps strongest in the realm of literature. As McKean observed, what sets literature apart from other arts is its moral essence. While moral standards might find no place in music or the like, they are as integral to literature as they are to life itself. To live is to navigate values, and literature resonates with us because of the values it reveals.

The land now known as Germany stands as a formidable force, a realm woven with a tapestry of culture stretching from the shadowed alps of München to the Baltic shores of Kiel. This same spirit breathes through Köln by the Rhine, across the heartlands to the Saxon bastion of Dresden upon the Elbe. It is a land of many sources, birthed from the bones of tribes long past.  

Germania, the cradle of the Germanic soul, whispers its origins in the halls of scholars and the minds of historians. Tacitus spoke of a tribe, the Tungrians, who bore the name before it crossed the Rhine to clash with Gaul. Julius Caesar, in his chronicles of the Gallic Wars, spoke of the Germans as those beyond the reach of Rome, a word borrowed from the Gauls to mark the boundary of conquest. The roots of the name are tangled and uncertain, some say it spoke of spears or the noise of battle, others of neighbors in a tongue long forgotten.  

Tacitus, that old chronicler, wrote of these people in his ancient tome, declaring them pure and unmingled with the world beyond. He pondered who would forsake the warmth of Asia or Africa for the cold embrace of Germania, a land wild and unyielding, save for those whose hearts called it home.  

And who would abandon Rome for such a place? Not the Romans, not then. They sent forth their legions to the edge of Germania in search of spoils, yet often returned to the heart of their empire. The Germanic tribes stood at the fringes, trading their goods and their strength, serving in the legions of Rome, a quiet presence on the edge of the world.

In the shadowy world of Twelfth Night, disguise weaves its crooked paths through hearts and minds, a tool as potent for deception as a serpent's bite. Yet, like all masks, it wears thin, and there comes a time when a soul must shed the borrowed skin or risk becoming a ghost of its own self. To peel away such layers can leave a person stranded, adrift from those they once held dear. The heart must choose between the essence of one's being and the fragile threads of connection, for though some may shrug off the trickery, others may find their trust shattered like glass upon the stones.

In the twisted dance of gender's guise, the stakes rise higher, for it stirs the question of why one would shun their face to don another's form. Viola steps into this masquerade, a shield against the perils of a strange land: "I’ll bring you to a captain in this town / Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help / I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). In her guise, she finds sanctuary, yet the cost is a severance from the sisterhood of women, a solitude deepened by Olivia's love, misled by the twin faces of Viola and Sebastian: "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138). Caught in this web, Viola must wrestle with the silent longing that stirs between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times / Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261).

In the eyes of today, Twelfth Night reveals how disguise can unearth the truths buried beneath propriety's surface, drawing out desires unspoken. Olivia and Orsino find themselves entangled in emotions that Viola's presence ignites. Does Olivia's heart beat for Cesario as a man, or does she yearn unawares for the woman beneath? The swift turn of her affections to Sebastian suggests a parody of those who judge by appearance alone, as Olivia declares the bond of kinship over passion: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315). Thus, the play unfolds, a mirror to the complexities of the human heart, where deception lays bare the truths we dare not speak.

The tales of German colonial rule are etched deep with the ink of brutality, a specter that looms large over the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in the land then known as German South West Africa. Yet to paint the expanse of a colonial empire with but a single brush would be folly. The German dominion, a mosaic of lands and peoples, bore witness to a tapestry of governance as diverse as the landscapes it encompassed. The promise and reality of education followed suit.

When the British set foot upon the remnants of German East Africa, which the world now knows as Tanganyika, in the year of 1919, they found among the people a surprising bloom of literacy and learning. It was a testament to German endeavors in the realm of education, which some chroniclers of the time did not hesitate to commend, not just in Tanganyika but in the distant reaches of Kamerun and beyond.

Yet in the lands of South West Africa, a harsher tale unfolded. Unlike their counterparts in the east, where the state's hand had shaped schools and guided the minds of the youth, here the education of the native was left to the fervor of missionary zeal, scantily aided by the government’s coffers. Indeed, the government reserved its resources for the education of Europeans, crafting schools of the state and casting a tighter rein on the mission schools that did exist. This divergence in policy left its mark long after the German banner was lowered. While other colonies could boast of learned natives, South West Africa remained largely a land of shadows, untouched by the light of education, its people unlettered and silent.

The reasons for this divergence are manifold, a knot of social, political, and economic threads. This discourse seeks to unravel these threads, to shed light on the attitudes of settlers and the powers that once claimed dominion over these lands. The chronicles of education in the German empire are numerous, penned mostly in the tongue of the empire itself, during or soon after its time of rule. At first, these works endeavored merely to sketch the contours of educational systems. But with time, writings in English broadened the horizon through comparative studies and deeper examinations of specific educational facets. These studies laid bare the stark differences that lay between the colonies.

The most notable work, Cohen’s study, delves into the heart of this paper’s inquiry, drawing comparisons between the systems that took root in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen argues that the settler population in South West Africa played a pivotal role in shaping the educational landscape of the colony.

South West Africa, by the grace of its temperate climes and despite the desert's embrace, attracted a European populace larger than most of Germany’s other distant possessions. In 1913, nearly fifteen thousand whites called it home, outnumbering those in East Africa, the next closest in settler count, where just over five thousand souls lived under the German sun.

The tale of two nations, the United States and Mexico, is one marked by a rivalry that spanned the years like a shadow cast long upon the land. It was a saga that stretched from the year of our Lord 1836 unto 1893, a span of fifty-seven years filled with strife and discord. The apex of this enmity was the war they called the Mexican-American War, fought between the years 1846 and 1848, where the United States, in its relentless march, did lay claim to the lands of Texas and the American Southwest, wresting them from the grasp of Mexico. Battles and skirmishes flared between these nations, a conflagration that found its peace only as the world edged toward the Great War. The roots of this contention lay deep in the soil of ideological and cultural divide, a clash of gods and traditions, a collision of material desires (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).
